        <h2 class="s-title">What Most<br>Visitors Miss</h2>
        <div class="hist-list">
          <div class="hist-entry">
            <div class="hist-cat">The Car Ban · 1898</div>
            <div class="hist-hed">It was a horse-protection ordinance, not environmentalism</div>
            <div class="hist-body">Resort owners banned cars because the noise frightened horses used by wealthy guests. An accident of equine property rights that shaped the island forever.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="hist-entry">
            <div class="hist-cat">Sociology</div>
            <div class="hist-hed">"Fudgies" — what workers call you</div>
            <div class="hist-body">~3,000 seasonal workers (mostly J-1 visas) run the island. They call tourists "fudgies." Not affectionate. The Grand Hotel ($800+/night, $10 to walk the porch) is a 5-min walk from the employee dorms.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="hist-entry">
            <div class="hist-cat">Fur Trade · 1780–1834</div>
            <div class="hist-hed">John Jacob Astor became America's richest man here</div>
            <div class="hist-body">Every beaver pelt destined for Europe passed through these straits. When silk hats replaced fur ones, the island pivoted to tourism in a single generation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

